args:
The Scroll reveals that the Goddess Ilia had a
daughter, leaving Nevin and Ramiel to weigh
what to do with that discovery. Elsewhere, as
Ilia thinks of Meene and why she penned the
Scrolls, Mordecai has a lovely answer.
(I knew these two were more than they\nseemed, but this is...)
Fight's over, pal. Give us the boy.
It's not over until I've had my turn.
We both know you can't beat us while\nprotecting him, so give it up.
Sorry, but my father raised me to keep\nmy promises.
And I promised to keep him\nand his mother safe.
Now stop worrying about me and let's go.
It's the Scrolls of Perdition you're after,\nright?
I have one of them here.
What?! How do YOU have it?!
The boy's mother gave it to me in return\nfor promising to protect her son.
It's fine. But in exchange, we get the boy.
And you'll promise not to get involved\nwith him or his mother ever again.
The Scroll is legitimate; I can sense the\nbroken seal upon it.
My memory isn't entirely clear, as it was\nover in a moment...
But when I passed that man before, I\nbelieve he had another woman at his side.
If that was this boy's mother,\ntheir story may well check out.
Still, it's not a decision I can just—
What?! Hey, hold on a minute, kid!\nWe got no idea what these folks here\nare really about.
I know. But I don't want you to fight\nany more.
We'll make sure he gets home safe.\nYou have my word on it.
All right, then. You take care.
I will. And thanks for keeping your\npromise to protect me.
You'd better get him back in one piece.
You just worry about your side of the\nbargain. Speaking of which...here.
The Scroll is yours now—just please\ndon't start any stupid wars with it.
The Goddess wouldn't have wanted that.
Scroll of Perdition secured.\nOur mission is complete.
Not quite the way I saw this going,\nbut I guess I'll take it.
Darling, you're safe! Oh, I was so worried!
'Cause I lost the present I bought you!\nI tried to find it, but I couldn't, and...and\nI got scared of going home without it.
I couldn't take the key to perdition,\nand I couldn't even get you a single\nlousy present!
I love you so much and I can't do\nANYTHING for you!
Oh, you fool of a child.
Have I ever once asked you to accept\nthe key from me?
I don't want freedom or safety at the cost\nof your own, Alfie. All I want in this life\nis for you to be happy.
You're the reason for my whole existence.\nYou're my hope.
Most who inherit the keyholders' bloodline\nare never permitted to live free.
They're born into a life of fugitive solitude\nin order to keep the Scrolls safe.
I lost both my parents young—too young—\nand the loneliness nearly broke me.
On the day I snapped and fled the barrier,\nI found a baby alone in the woods.
From that day on, you have been the light\nof my life; I only survived until now\nbecause of the hope you gave me.
I'm sorry, Mom! I'm so sorry!
Just promise not to leave me again—\nat least not until you're a man grown.
Alfie, is there any chance this is the\npresent you dropped?
Wha?! How do YOU have it?!
Here, Mom! This is for you!
You couldn't ask for a happier ending\non Dragonyule.
But are you certain it was all right\nto give them the Scroll?

Oh, I'd prefer to have destroyed it, but I
already memorized what it said—and even
if it does go public, there's nothing in
there that's too terribly dangerous.
Stuff you and I already know, mostly.
But as for what those two will do with it,\nthe Goddess only knows.
It says She wished for the happiness of\nHer first child—Her lost daughter—\nuntil her very last breath.
I thought the Goddess's kid was the Other.\nIs this that?
Who can say? Perhaps she had a second\nchild.
Or maybe this Scroll is not the book of\nrevelation we thought it to be?
This is more of a diary—a personal record \nwhich we have somehow spun a grand\nfantasy around.
And that strange girl's words ring truer\nhaving read it.
What, about how the Goddess wouldn't\nhave wanted a war fought over this?
She made it sound like she knew\nthe big lady personally.
I thought the same. And though I do not\nknow who or what she is, I find myself\nagreeing with her claim.
The Goddess would surely never want the\nlove she bore her child to be the spark that\nset the world ablaze.
Her daughter probably wouldn't be too\nthrilled about it either.
Which brings us to the question of what\nthe hell we're supposed to do with this.
I worry that's going to be harder than it\nwas to track the damn thing down in the\nfirst place.
Well, I'll be. It's Dragonyule Eve.
You hungry, Ramiel? I know I always\nthink better on a full stomach.
If I didn't know better, Nevin, I'd think you\njust want to spend Dragonyule with me.
For all your protestations of being a grown\nman, that's actually rather adorable.
Here I go making a heartfelt gesture\nand you mock me for it? The nerve!
My apologies. Let us put jesting aside\nand go enjoy a meal together.
There's no telling how many more\nDragonyules we'll get, after all.
Yeah, taking one night for a little\nfather-son bonding won't bring\na lightning bolt down on our heads.
(I'm glad to hear you passed on\nsurrounded by people who loved you.)
(You just wanted the best for your sorry\nexcuse for a daughter, right to the end.)
Ilia, it's about time we headed into...
Can you blame me? It's a thousand years\nlater and here I've felt her love again,\nas overprotective as ever.
Guess it got me feeling nostalgic.\n...And happy. ...And also guilty.
I don't regret leaving her side to be here,\nbut I'm also not totally sure that was the\nright decision to make.
Looking back now, with the choice I made,\nI can only speak in terms of the results.
But I don't want to reduce the feelings and\nresolve of that moment to results. I mean,\nwhat's even the point of that?
I know there's no getting at the ＂right\nanswer,＂ but... Well, sometimes I just\nwant to see her again SO badly.
I want to hear her say my name.
Ilia, why do you think Meene left the\nScrolls of Perdition behind?
Dunno. Maybe she wanted to leave some\nrecord of the true history of the world?
That could be part of it, yes.
What, you think there's more to it?
You know, you're a genius when it comes\nto everything but yourself.
Or is that just what family's like?\nToo close to each another to see clearly?
You want to get to your point, wise guy,\nor are you just teasing me?
Meene would have understood that leaving\na record of the truth would cause chaos in\nfuture generations.
But she did it anyway, even going so far\nas to task bloodlines she trusted to hide\naway the keys to its unsealing.
What reason would she have to insist\nthat strongly on an accurate history\nbeing preserved?
Hey, yeah. I mean, she went as far as to\ntake on my name and save the world,\nbut the Scrolls reveal her as a fraud.
What if the Scrolls of Perdition were her\nmessage to you?
A way to show she never forgot us.\nA way to leave some small token behind.
What if that is the Scrolls' true purpose?
Believing that one day, in some world,\nwe would find the writings she left us.
Perhaps that faith is what led her\nto do this.
You really think she'd do all that for a\nselfish brat like me?
You know better than anyone the sort of\nwoman Meene was.
If we ever get the chance to meet again,\nI'm going to take the chance to tell her\nMY feelings.
Yeah. Some day, we'll go back.\nTogether.
(I'll say it when I get back, Meene:\nThank you for the Dragonyule miracle.)
